        title: "What is an ISMS?",
        content:
          "An Information Security Management System (ISMS) is a complete framework of policies and procedures for systematically managing your organisation's information security.\n\nAn ISMS thrives on constant review and development. This gives you the opportunity to identify new threats and risks in time to protect your business before it's too late.\n\n**An ISMS typically has three main protection objectives:**\n\n*   **Confidentiality: Keeping information and data private.**\n    \n*   **Availability: Ensuring that information & systems are available when needed.**\n    \n*   **Integrity: Ensuring that information can be trusted and is not manipulated.**\n    \n\nDepending on the level of security you can achieve and where your priorities lie, your ISMS will be individually designed to meet these objectives at a level that is appropriate for you.\n\n> For example: Very high availability may be necessary for someone who processes orders for a shop around the clock, but not for a design agency that does not usually need to process requests in a matter of seconds.\n\nMost industries have agreed on standards for the design of an ISMS to ensure a comparable outcome and the ability to have an ISMS audited by an independent party.\n\n*   **ISO® 27001:** This is the most widely used international standard for information security. It can be implemented in not-for-profit, public and private organisations. It is a risk-based system, so many decisions can be based on an organisation's individual risk situation. This idea is rooted in many other information security standards, which are often based on the 27001.",
