          "**Implementation**  \nTo begin implementing the ISMS, start with the chapters from Section 4 onward. Each chapter provides specific explanations and mentions the required documentation you need to apply in your organization. Always keep your assessment objectives in mind as you proceed.\n\n* * *\n\n**Check Progress**  \nWhile implementing your ISMS, it is important to track progress and evaluate your implementation status. Use the following documents to facilitate this process:\n\n*   **Evaluation of Norm Compliance**:  \n    This internal document is used to assess the implementation of the management system outlined in chapters 4–10 (Harmonized Structure).\n    \n*   **Statement of Applicability (SoA)**:  \n    This document helps verify the implementation of controls in the Appendix. It also serves as the official ISMS document describing your control implementation (explained in detail in Chapter 6.1.3).\n    \n\n* * *\n\n**Documentation**  \nBefore implementing the documents, start by editing the **Document Control** policy to define how documents will be managed. This ensures that all documents and guidelines:\n\n*   Are always up-to-date.\n    \n*   Follow a uniform and repeatable structure.\n    \n*   Guarantee the secure and consistent handling of all organizational documents.\n    \n\nIt is advisable to establish where and how documents will be managed before implementation begins. Consider using tools like Confluence or SharePoint to streamline documentation management.\n\n* * *\n\n**The Action Plan**  \nYour ISMS will require you to perform specific tasks, some on a recurring basis and others as one-time actions. Use the **Action Plan Template** to document and organize these tasks.\n\nWhile you may choose to manage tasks within a software tool of your choice, ensure that planned tasks are clearly documented in the Action Plan template. This will be referenced repeatedly in the ISMS Guide. Proper documentation of planned tasks and timely execution will ensure a smoother audit process.",
