        content:
          "🔎 Understand\n-------------\n\n> _The organization shall determine the boundaries and applicability of the information security management system to establish its scope._\n> \n> _When determining this scope, the organization shall consider:_\n> \n> _a) the external and internal issues referred to in 4.1;_  \n> _b) the requirements referred to in 4.2;_  \n> _c) interfaces and dependencies between activities performed by the organization, and those that are performed by other organizations._\n> \n> _The scope shall be available as documented information._\n> \n> **_ISO® 27001_**\n\nDefining the scope of your ISMS is a very important topic. It reflects the exact boundaries and the area of application of your ISMS.\n\nThe full description of the scope is in the referenced documents, but as an example we described these scenarios for you:\n\n> **Simple Scope:** Your organization has 50 employees that consult customers on IT-related questions. As you want to ensure a high standard of information security, you implement the ISMS for the complete organization without exceptions.\n\n> **Narrowed Scope:** Your organization is a big corporation with different locations and business areas. On your location in Berlin, you are responsible for constructing CAD Data for a specific set of customers. These customers request a certification. For now, the ISMS shall only apply to this business area & location to keep costs and complexity low.\n\n> **Narrowed Scope but complicated:** Same as above, but because of an old contract, some data will be forwarded from an office in Brussel which can not easily be included in the scope. Your scope will describe this interface and you will ensure, that this process is respected in your ISMS procedures.\n\n> **Mixed Scope:** Your organization wants to get high risk business areas as well as the complete IT operation covered by the ISMS. Therefore, your ISMS will cover specific business areas and all IT-structure. Therefore low risk business areas are not object to policies. Because your IT is in the scope, some IT rules (like handling of suspicious E-Mails) are still applied to these employees.\n\nIn most cases, a Simple scope is the way to go.\n\n**Got a question on the Scope? Feel free to ask in the Community!**\n\n\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\n\n✅ Implement\n-----------\n\n**We provided some documents for you that you can find in the documents area of Cybermap:**\n\n*   [Definition of Scope](https://cybermap.circle.so/c/all-documents/definition-of-scope)\n    \n\n**Make sure to implement as follows:**\n\n*   Make sure that the Definition of Scope includes a throughout description of your individual situation and the exact norm version you target a certification for.\n    \n*   Please check your defined scope with other requirements as documented in 4.1 and 4.2 to ensure a fitting scope definition.",
